{"id":"cpot","version":"0.0.1","templates":[{"id":"cpot","version":"0.1.0"}],"language":"en","updated":"2021-09-21T14:53:15+02:00","authors":[{"name":"Maryam Razavi","email":"maryam.razavi@cambio.se"}],"format":"CambioForm.v1","name":"cpot","actions":[{"condition":"patient_intubated=='at0013'","assignments":["compliance_with_the.hidden=true",""],"otherwise":["compliance_with_the.hidden=false",""]},{"condition":"patient_intubated=='at0014'","assignments":["vocalization.hidden=true"],"otherwise":["vocalization.hidden=false"]},{"condition":"!total_score","assignments":["interpretation.hidden=true","management.hidden=true"],"otherwise":["interpretation.hidden=false","management.hidden=false"]}],"guidelines":[{"condition":"","execution":[{"id":"CPOT","version":"1"}]}],"elements":[{"type":"form","children":[{"type":"container","children":[{"type":"row","spanlarge":12,"spanmedium":8,"spansmall":4,"children":[{"type":"column","spanlarge":12,"spanmedium":8,"spansmall":4,"children":[{"type":"text","text":"**Critical Care Pain Observation Tool (CPOT)**\n\nRates critically ill patients’ pain based on clinical observation.\n\n**Use**\n\nThe CPOT can be used to assess intubated or sedated patients pain based on facial expressions, muscle tension and movement as well as compliance with ventilated breaths for intubated patients or vocalized pain for non-intubated patients.\n\n**Pitfalls**\n\n- The gold standard of pain assessment is patient’s self-reported pain.\n- CPOT scores were higher when conscious and intubated than when unconscious or extubated, which is thought to be due to endotracheal tube discomfort or positive pressure causing incision site pain.\n- CPOT scores were similar for unconscious and conscious extubated patients which may be due to lingering anesthesia or pain resolution from extubation.\n\n\n\n**Formula**\n\nAddition of selected points."}]}]},{"type":"row","spanlarge":12,"spanmedium":8,"spansmall":4,"children":[{"type":"column","spanlarge":6,"spanmedium":4,"s